page.title: 09AREAS OF INTEREST PETT LEVEL
page.content: Elm trees have been removed from Straem Lane at the eastern edge of Fairlight, victims of{Dutch elm {disease. Between the Haddocks and Pett Level{ there is a landscape of wooded cliff top unique to the coastline. Plants there include ferns (Harts Tongue, Hard and Male), Muscatel, Stinking Iris, Butcher's Broom and Common Spotted Orchids. Monterey Pines on the cliff top date, with the houses they surround, from the 1930's. Stumblet Wood is basically of oak and houses marsh tits, treecreepers, jays, nuthatches and tawney owls. Badger, fox and rabbit are common in the area. {Wetlands:}Magpie's Hall (a joke name for unproductive land) is simply a flooded alder coppice.
